BSE - France (07) 980324230947
Date: Wed, 25 Mar 1998 11:09:30 +0100
From: Jeanne Brugere-Picoux <jbrugere@vet-alfort.fr>

The exact reference for "un cas de tremblante sur un boeuf" is "Revue de
medecine veterinaire, 1883,7,310-313 and the author was a veterinarian,
Sarradet. The first clinical sign was prurit in this case with an evolution
to paralysis. Without histology - the first description of histopathology of
scrapie was made by the French Besnoit (veterinarian) and Morel in 1898 - we
cannot say that it is surely BSE but the veterinarian Sarradet conclude that
it was "scrapie".
The hypothesis of sporadic BSE in the world (like sporadic or familial
Creutfedt-Jakob disease) is credible. I am not sure that the origin of BSE
in United-Kindom was a ovine strain of scrapie but we don't know. The
concept that some sporadic CJD in humans might long have had a dietary
origin is also plausible. This concept prove that the transmission is rarely
seen when ther is not an "infectious pressure".
There is probably very sporadic cases of BSE in some part of the world (very
difficult to find because we know the difficulties of the diagnosis and of
the declaration of BSE). For exemple, remember the suspicion in 1985 of BSE
[actually a putative bovine TSE, not BSE which is presently specific
European disease in "downers cows" in USA (with natural contamination of
Mink).
--
