Date: Wed, 25 Mar 1998 06:46:38 +0100
From: Kari Koster-Losche <loesche@flensburg.netsurf.de>
Source: Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy <BSE-L@RZ.UNI-KARLSRUHE.DE>

Tom wrote:
>> -- In the last days of the month of November 1881, this animal began to
experience an intense inching at the base of the neck, which it scratched
against all the objects that it found in its stall. In the barn, it rubbed
with a veritable furor against the stall or against its restraint; in the
pasture, against all the trees that it could find; shackled, against the
front part of the post where, if it could not reach, it contorted itself to
scratch against the stanchion.<<
---snip---
It seems that francophone cattle are prone to scratching symptoms. :-)
5% of the Swiss BSE cattle showed severe scratching symptoms, 17% milder
ones. (BOVINE SPONGIFORM ENCEPHALOPATHY (BSE): CLINICAL SIGNS IN SWISS BSE
CASES; B. Hoernlimann and U. Brown; 1994). The authors state that this sign
was typical
for Swiss BSE cases.
I fear scratching indicates that the agent has wandered from the central
nervous system to the periphery (skin). This would imply an increased risk
for the gelatine production of skins.
--
Kari Koster-Losche
e-mail: loesche@flensburg.netsurf.de
